{"id":"br-b01","title":"Preserve projects/*/memory/ dirs â€” auto-memory files must survive the reset","description":"auto-memory files in ~/.claude/projects/*/memory/ (e.g. MEMORY.md) are the persistent memory across sessions. The CLI owns ~/.claude/ and may reset it. These files must be backed up to ~/claude/ (git-tracked) and restored/linked back after any reset. This is the highest-priority preserve task since memory loss is the most impactful.","acceptance_criteria":"MEMORY.md and other memory files are canonical in ~/claude/. Symlink or hard link from ~/.claude/projects/*/memory/ points to ~/claude/ copies. Survives a full rm -rf ~/.claude/ + CLI re-init cycle. csync.sh or equivalent captures changes.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-20T12:54:35.737057799Z","created_by":"skogix","updated_at":"2026-02-21T14:44:10.744718912Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["critical","migration","preserve"]}
{"id":"br-ch2","title":"go over the workflow we would need for git add -A at the start of the users turn. he do the changes and a git diff vs git diff --cached is the changes + intent in message itself","description":"Design a workflow where git add -A runs at the start of the user's turn (via hook). This captures any manual file changes the user made outside claude. Then git diff shows the user's manual changes as context, and git diff --cached shows staged changes. The user's message + the diff together form the full intent signal for the session.","acceptance_criteria":"Hook runs git add -A on UserPromptSubmit (or similar). git diff (unstaged) and git diff --cached (staged) are both meaningful. Workflow documented. Does not interfere with csync.sh auto-commit flow.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-02-20T23:36:19.051662524Z","created_by":"skogix","updated_at":"2026-02-21T14:44:15.219823991Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["design","workflow"]}
